Targeting A Housing Subsidy

Shengao Yi

October 29, 2022

1. Introduction

The Department of Housing and Community Development (HCD) has launched a tax credit program for nearly twenty years. HCD tries their best to proactively reach out to eligible homeowners ever year, but the uptake of the credit is woefully inadequate. HCD thinks the low conversion rate is due to the fact that the agency reaches out to eligible homeowners at random. The cost of marketing material allocation is $2,850 per year and the credit cost is $5,000. According to the researchers in Philadelphia, houses that transacted after taking the credit, sold with a $10,000 premium, on average. Also homes surrounding the repaired home see an aggregate premium of $56,000, on average. So the target of this project is to train a best classifier and use the results to inform a cost/benefit analysis.

2. Data Visualization

This section contains some data visualizations, indicating the characteristics of homeowners who has or hasn’t taken the tax credit. For the continuous features, there are some interesting phenomena. “Previous” feature is the the number of contacts for an individual prior to the tax credit program, which shows that the more times someone gets contacts, they are more likely to take the tax credit. “Campaign” feature is the the number of contacts for an individual within the duration tax credit program, which indicates that the more times they have been contacted, they are more likely to not participate in the tax credit program. There is an obvious difference in the unemployment rate feature and inflation rate. People usually take the credit when the unemployment rate is high or inflation rate is high. Similar in other continuous features.

housingSubsidy %>%

Now let’s look at the categorical features. It seems that if someone has a mortgage, they won’t take tax credit compared to those without a mortgage. And also if the owner’s full time residence not in Philadelphia, they won’t be involved in the program.

For the remaining categorical features, we can find that there is no obvious difference in many features. But we should note that whose people who were contacted on a cellphone rather than telephone, who works in administration, gets married, higher education are more likely to take tax credit.

3. Model Building & Cost-Benefit Analysis

3.1 Reclassify the Category Data

Due to a large number of types in some categorical features, we can reclassify them and create new dataset.

Season: We can categorize the months into four season: Winter, Spring, Summer and Fall.

Education Level: We can categorize the education level into four categories: Elementary School, High School, Higher Education and Illiterate.

Contact: We can categorize the number of days into weeks.

Employment: We can categorize the employment status into unemploy, retired and employ.

# Season
housingSubsidy <-
  housingSubsidy %>%
  mutate(Season = case_when(
    month == "dec" | month == "jan" | month == "feb" ~ "Winter",
    month == "mar" | month == "apr" | month == "may" ~ "Spring",
    month == "jun" | month == "jul" | month == "aug" ~ "Summer",
    month == "sep" | month == "oct" | month == "nov" ~ "Fall"))

# Previous Contact
housingSubsidy <-
  housingSubsidy %>%
  mutate(Contact = case_when(
    pdays == 999 ~ "No Contact",
    pdays < 7 ~ "1 week",
    pdays >= 7 & pdays < 14 ~ "2 Weeks",
    pdays >= 15 & pdays < 21 ~ "3 Weeks",
    pdays >= 22 ~ "More than 3 Weeks"))

# Education Classification
housingSubsidy <-
  housingSubsidy %>%
  mutate(Education = case_when(
    education == "basic.9y" |education == "basic.6y" | education == "basic.4y" ~ "Elementary School",
    education == "high.school"  ~ "High School",
    education == "university.degree" |education == "professional.course"  ~ "Higher Education",
    education == "unknown" |education == "illiterate"  ~ "Illiterate"))

# Employment Status
housingSubsidy <- 
  housingSubsidy %>% 
  mutate(EmploymentStatus = case_when(
    job == "student" | job == "unemployed" ~ "unemployed",
    job == "retired" ~ "retired",
    TRUE  ~ "employed"))

3.2 Training/Testing sets

Then, we created the training and test sets. CreateDataPartition is used to split the data. A 65% sample is used here to reduce processing time.

set.seed(3456)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(housingSubsidy$X, p = .65,
                                  list = FALSE,
                                  times = 1)
housingSubsidyTrain <- housingSubsidy[ trainIndex,]
housingSubsidyTest  <- housingSubsidy[-trainIndex,]

3.3 Model Evaluation

In this section, we have run two different regression models, kitchen sink and feature engineered model. The kitchen sink model contains all the original data while excluding the engineered features. The feature engineered model includes the new reclassified features except for the original data.

For the kitchen sink model, we get a McFadden score of 0.224, AIC is 1548.6. For the feature engineered model, the McFadden score is 0.201, AIC is 1557.4. The McFadden score is a metric of goodness for fit, which is demonstrated - the higher, the better. So the kitchen sink is better fit than the engineered model. To improve the McFadden score of engineered model, we have made a lot of trials, but the kitchen sink model is still better. Considering that there is no significant difference between the two models, we use the engineered model for further study.

# Kitchen sink
housingSubsidy_kitchensink <- glm(y_numeric ~ .,
                  data = housingSubsidyTrain %>%  
                    dplyr::select(-Education, -Season, -Contact, -EmploymentStatus, -X, -y),
                  family="binomial" (link="logit"))

3.4 Cross validation

Then, we use cross validation tool to test the model’s performance, set 100 folds. The facetted plots of ROC, Sensitivity and Specificity are shown below. In general, the tighter each distribution is to its mean, the more generalizable the model in each calculation. For ROC, it seems that the Feature Engineered model is slightly better than the Kitchen Sink model. In both models, the sensitivity is similar and almost perfect, which means both models are good at predicting true positive results. And in specificity, maybe Kitchen Sink model performs better than Feature Engineered model.

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 100, classProbs=TRUE, summaryFunction=twoClassSummary)

cvFit_kitchensink <- train(y ~ .,
                  data = housingSubsidy %>% 
                    dplyr::select(-Education, -Season, -Contact, -EmploymentStatus, -X, -y_numeric), 
                method="glm", family="binomial",
                metric="ROC", trControl = ctrl)

cvFit_engineered <- train(y ~ .,
                  data = housingSubsidy %>% 
                    na.omit() %>%
                    dplyr::select(-month, -education, -pdays, -job, -y_numeric, -X), 
                method="glm", family="binomial",
                metric="ROC", trControl = ctrl)

3.5 Predictions

After obtaining the models, we can make predictions of taking the tax credit. A negative value or 0 means they did not take the tax credit. In general, a good model will have a peak near 0 for the negatives (no tax credit), and a peak close to 1 for the positives (take tax credit). In Figure 6, we can find that our model is better at predicting the negatives rather than the positives.

testProbs <- data.frame(Outcome = as.factor(housingSubsidyTest$y_numeric),
                        Probs = predict(housingSubsidy_engineered, housingSubsidyTest, type= "response"))

ggplot(testProbs, aes(x = Probs, fill = as.factor(Outcome))) +
  geom_density() +
  facet_grid(Outcome ~ .) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = palette2) + xlim(0, 1) +
  labs(x = "Credit", y = "Density of probabilities",
       title = "Figure 6: Distribution of predicted probabilities by observed outcome") +
  plotTheme() + theme(strip.text.x = element_text(size = 18),
        legend.position = "none")

3.6 Confusion Matrix

The confusion matrix for the threshold of 50% shows us the rate at which we got True Positives (Sensitivity), False Positives, True Negatives (Specificity) and False Negatives for that threshold.

testProbs <-

  mutate(predOutcome  = as.factor(ifelse(testProbs$Probs > 0.5 , 1, 0)))

3.7 ROC Curve

Then, we use the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve as the goodness of fit metric, since it visualizes the trade-offs for two important confusion metrics, while also providing a single goodness of fit indicator. The y-axis of the ROC curve shows the rate of true positives for each threshold from 0.01 to 1. The x-axis shows the rate of false positives for each threshold. The usefulness of the algorithm can be judged by the proportion of the plotting area that is under the ROC curve. The Area Under the Curve (AUC) curve for our model is 0.776, indicating that we have a strong model with the feature engineered variables.

ggplot(testProbs, aes(d = as.numeric(testProbs$Outcome), m = Probs)) +
  geom_roc(n.cuts = 50, labels = FALSE, colour = "#FE9900") +
  style_roc(theme = theme_grey) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0, size = 1.5, color = 'grey') +
  labs(title = "Figure 7: ROC Curve - Tax Credit")

pROC::auc(testProbs$Outcome, testProbs$Probs)

3.8 Cost/Benefit analysis

In the final, our aim is to create a cost-benefit analysis, in order to optimize the resource distribution and move toward a more targeted campaign.

We have the following assumptions about the marketing campaign:

  • Marketing Resources Cost: $2,850

  • Credit Cost: $5,000

  • Houses that transacted after taking the credit, sold with a $10,000 premium, on average.

  • Homes surrounding the repaired home see an aggregate premium of $56,000, on average.

Through these assumptions, below the cost/benefit for each outcome in our confusion matrix is calculated:

True Negative Revenue: Predicted correctly homeowner would not take the credit, no marketing resources were allocated, and no credit was allocated. Count * 0.

True Positive Revenue: Predicted correctly homeowner would enter credit program; allocated the marketing resources, and 25% ultimately achieved the credit:

  • Marketing Cost: -$2,850 * Count;

  • Credit Cost: -$5,000 * Count * 0.25;

  • Houses Premium: +$10,000 * Count * 0.25;

  • Neighborhood Premium: +$56,000 * Count * 0.25.

False Negative Revenue: We predicted that a homeowner would not take the credit but they did. These are likely homeowners who signed up for reasons unrelated to the marketing campaign. Thus, we ‘0 out’ this category, assuming the cost/benefit of this is $0.

False Positive Revenue: Predicted incorrectly homeowner would take the credit; allocated marketing resources; no credit allocated.

  • Marketing Cost: -$2,850 * Count;

In our analysis, the revenue is 0$ in true_negative and false_negative, which means the department doesn’t lose money. As the threshold value increases, false_positive revenue gradually rises and true_positive falls, eventually converging to 0.

iterateThresholds <- function(data) {
  x = .01
  all_prediction <- data.frame()
  while (x <= 1) {
  
  this_prediction <-
      testProbs %>%
      mutate(predOutcome = ifelse(Probs > x, 1, 0)) %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
     gather(Variable, Count) %>%
     mutate(Revenue =
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Negative", (Count * 0),
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive", (Count * (-2850) + (-5000) * (Count * .25) + (Count * .25) * 10000 + (Count * .25) * 56000),
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", (Count * 0),
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", (Count * -2850), 0)
               )
               )
               ),
            Threshold = x)
  all_prediction <- rbind(all_prediction, this_prediction)
  x <- x + .01
  }
return(all_prediction)
}

whichThreshold <- iterateThresholds(testProbs)

whichThreshold_revenue <- 
  whichThreshold %>% 
  group_by(Threshold) %>% 
  summarize(Revenue = sum(Revenue))

whichThreshold %>%
  ggplot(.,aes(Threshold, Revenue, colour = Variable)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_colour_manual(values = palette5[c(5, 1:3)]) +    
  labs(title = "Figure 9: Revenue by confusion matrix type and threshold",
       y = "Revenue") +
  plotTheme() +
  guides(colour=guide_legend(title = "Confusion Matrix"))

As seen in Figure 10, the total revenues increase from the threshold of 0 and peaks at 0.18, then decrease slowly 0 revenue. This means that if the department wants to maximize their revenue, they should only allocate to those in the thresholds near 0.18. For the total count of credits, we can see from Figure 11 that it keeps rising gradually until around threshold of 0.84 and then remains stable.

whichThreshold_revenue <-

                         ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", Count, 0))) %>%

4. Conclustion

In conclusion, I will recommend this model to the Department of Housing and Community Development. The feature engineered model is good at predicting the true positives, which means the homeowners who will take the tax credit. But there are still some shorcomings of the model. Figure 9 shows that a lot of money is spent or lost on homeowners in the false positives, and the low specificity rate. So this model has the potential to improve. Maybe we can introduce some spatial features like where the houses locate, the income, racial characteristics and so on.

In addition, according to our findings, HCD should follow these strategies to attract more people to participate in this project:

  • Reach out to homeowners via cellphone instead of telephone.

  • Reach out to those who are married.

  • Reach out to those employed in administration.

  • Reach out to those received higher education.

  • Intensify marketing campaigns when the unemployment rates is high.
